model_completion: Born in 1908, Edward R. Murrow was an American journalist who is best known for his work on radio and television. He worked for CBS News from 1940 until 1961. His most famous broadcasts were the 'See It Now' series, which focused on McCarthyism. In 1954, he received a Peabody Award for his work. He died in 1965.

Born in 1923, Stephanie Kwolek was the daughter of immigrants from China. She grew up in Pennsylvania and studied chemistry at the Carnegie Institute of Technology (now Carnegie Mellon University). In 1960, she joined DuPont, where she developed the first synthetic fibre that would be stronger than steel, but lighter and more flexible. This fiber, Kevlar, has since been used in bulletproof vests, helmets, and other military equipment. It is also used in tires and car parts.

Harvey Bernard Milk was born in New York, and moved to San Francisco, California in the early 1970s. In 1976, he became the first openly gay politician elected to public office in California. He served as the first openly gay councilman for San Francisco from 1978-1983, and was assassinated in 1978. Harvey Milk Day was declared in California on May 22, 2009.

Born in Jamshedpur, India in 1982, Priyanka Chopra was the first child of her parents. At age 13, she moved to the U.S., where she attended school and participated in beauty pageants. In 2000, she returned to India and began a modeling career, which led to acting roles. Her first film role was in 'Thamizhan' (2002). She then starred in several Bollywood films, including 'Aitraaz' (2004), 'Dostana' (2008), 'Fashion' (2008) and 'Barfi!' (2012). She also made her American debut with the TV series 'Quantico,' which ran for three seasons.

Born in Tehran, Iran in 1955, Darius Khondji began his career as a photographer at age 18. In 1976, he moved to Paris, where he worked as a fashion photographer. In 1983, Khondji directed his first short film. His first feature film was 'Deliverance,' which was released in 1984. The film won several awards and was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film. In 1990, Khondji directed 'The Naked Kiss.' He has also directed the films 'Seven' and 'Mimic.'

Evo Morales is the president of Bolivia, and was elected to office in 2006. He is a socialist politician who has been involved in politics for many years, and is known for his opposition to neoliberal policies. In 1987, he founded the coca farmers' union, and in 2005, he became president of Bolivia. As president, he has implemented many reforms that have made life better for the people of Bolivia.

Born in 1732, George Washington was the first president of the United States and the commander-in-chief of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War. He served as president from 1789 to 1797. As a young man, he became an officer in the British army. In 1754, he married Martha Dandridge Custis. He fought in the French and Indian War, and in 1775, he became the first commander-in-chief of the Continental Army. After the war, he served as president of the Constitutional Convention.

Born in Mexico City in 1907, Frida Kahlo was the daughter of a German father and a Mexican mother. In 1925, she contracted polio, which left her with a weakened right leg. She later suffered a severe accident when she was hit by a bus at the age of 18, causing severe injuries to her pelvis and spine. She underwent numerous surgeries throughout her life, but the accident had a major impact on her life, as it led to her lifelong struggle with pain and disability. Her early works were influenced by Mexican folk art and traditional crafts, but she soon developed a unique style, incorporating elements from the Mexican muralists, such as Diego Rivera, David Alfaro Siqueiros, and Jose Clemente Orozco.

Žižek is a Slovenian philosopher and cultural theorist, who is best known for his work on psychoanalysis and critical theory. He was born in Ljubljana, Slovenia, on March 10, 1949, and has lived in London since 2003. His most famous book, The Sublime Object of Ideology (1989), is an analysis of the ideological dimension of everyday life. He is currently a professor at the European Graduate School and a visiting professor at the University of Paris-VIII.

Alvin Ailey was born on January 5, 1931 in Rogers, Texas, to Lula and Alvin Ailey, Sr. He attended the St. Mark's Church school, where he began studying dance. In 1948, he enrolled at Fisk University in Nashville, Tennessee, where he continued his studies of dance, as well as music and theatre. He moved to New York City in 1953, and in 1954, he formed the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater. The group has toured internationally and has been featured in several Broadway shows. Ailey was married to dancer Judith Jamison, with whom he had a daughter named Mary Alice. He died on December 1, 1989.

Born in Seoul, Korea, in 1986, Yuna Kim started skating at the age of 4. At 15, she was chosen to be on the Korean National Team, and at 17, she won her first Olympic medal, a silver in the women's singles at the 2006 Torino Winter Olympics. She has also won two World Championships (2006 and 2009), two Four Continents Championships (2007 and 2010), and four Grand Prix Finals (2007, 2008, 2011, and 2012). In 2007, Kim became the first woman to land a triple axel in competition.

Jackie Chan was born in Hong Kong in 1954, the son of a cook and a stuntman. At age 7, Jackie was introduced to martial arts by his father, who taught him the art of Wing Chun. In 1962, Jackie started performing at the age of 8, and continued his training at the China Drama Academy. His career took off when he appeared in the film 'New Fist of Fury' in 1972, which led to many more films, including 'The Big Boss,' 'Enter the Dragon,' and 'Rumble in the Bronx.' He also starred in 'Rush Hour' and 'Shanghai Noon.'

Marie Curie was born in Poland in 1867, the daughter of a physician. She married Pierre Curie in 1895 and they had two daughters together, Irene and Eve. In 1898, Marie Curie discovered polonium and radium, and in 1903, she discovered radioactivity. She also made many discoveries in chemistry and physics. She won the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1903, and in Chemistry in 1911. Marie Curie died in 1934 from leukemia caused by her exposure to radiation.

Karl Marx was born in Trier, Germany on May 5, 1818. His father, Heinrich, was a lawyer and his mother, Henriette, was a devout Lutheran. In 1836, he enrolled at the University of Bonn and later at the University of Berlin. He graduated from the university in 1841 and moved to Paris to pursue his studies in philosophy. In 1843, he married Jenny von Westphalen, who became his life-long companion. In 1848, he returned to Germany and joined the Communist League. In 1849, he wrote the 'Communist Manifesto' with Friedrich Engels. In 1867, he published the 'Das Kapital,' which became a classic work on capitalism. In 1871, Marx died in London at the age of 64.

Rachel Anne Maddow was born in Castro Valley, California on April 1, 1973. She attended Stanford University and earned her bachelor's degree in public policy. After graduation, she moved to New York City where she worked as a research assistant at the Oxford University Press. In 2004, Maddow became the host of 'The Rachel Maddow Show,' which airs on MSNBC. The show is known for its liberal perspective, and has been nominated for several Emmy awards. Maddow also hosts a podcast called 'Maddow Blog,' and has written two best-selling books, 'Drift' and 'Drift.'

Jamie Oliver was born in Essex, England in 1975. He attended the University of Westminster and then went to work as a chef. In 1998, he opened his first restaurant in London. The restaurant became so popular that it was featured in the British TV series 'The Naked Chef.' In 2004, he published a cookbook called 'Jamie's Dinners,' which became a best-seller in the U.K. In 2005, he appeared in 'The Naked Chef' television show in the United States, and in 2011, he hosted his own show on Food Network, 'Jamie Oliver's Food Revolution.' He has also starred in many other shows and has won several awards for his work.

John Maynard Keynes was born in Cambridge, England, on June 5, 1883. His father was a professor of economics at the University of Cambridge, and his mother was an artist. He went to Eton College and then studied at King's College, Cambridge, where he received a degree in economics. After graduating from college, he became a lecturer in economics at King's College, Cambridge, in 1909. In 1910, he married Lydia Lopokova, who was a Russian ballerina. During World War I, he worked as a researcher for the British Treasury, and then as an economic adviser to the British government. He died on April 21, 1946, at the age of 63.

Born in 1852, Edward Alexander Bouchet was the first African American to earn a Ph.D. from Yale University in 1876. After receiving his doctorate, he taught at Wilberforce College in Ohio. In 1879, he became the first African American to earn a master's degree from Yale, and later in 1880, he received a doctorate in physics from the university. He went on to teach physics at the University of Michigan and Howard University. Bouchet also wrote two books: 'The Color Problem,' and 'The Race Question.' He died in 1918.

Hammurabi was the sixth king of Babylon and ruled from 1792 to 1750 BCE. He is considered one of the greatest lawgivers of antiquity, because he codified the laws of ancient Mesopotamia into the Code of Hammurabi. The code included 282 laws on civil, criminal, and commercial matters.

Born in Ulm, Germany, in 1879, Albert Einstein was the son of a Jewish engineer and a Catholic mother. At age 16, Einstein left home to study science at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology. In 1905, Einstein published four papers that revolutionized physics. He won the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1921. His theories on relativity were so influential that he became known as the 'father of modern physics.'

Born in Bonn, Germany, on December 16, 1770, Ludwig van Beethoven was a German composer and pianist, whose work has influenced many composers including Chopin, Liszt, Schubert, Brahms, Tchaikovsky, Debussy, Rachmaninoff, and Mahler. He was the son of a court musician who had been appointed to the post by the Archduke Maximilian of Austria, and he began his musical education at age six. In 1792, Beethoven moved to Vienna, where he became a well-known piano virtuoso, and was introduced to Haydn, Mozart, and Salieri. In 1802, Beethoven's hearing began to deteriorate. Despite this, he continued to write music until his death in 1827.

Toni Morrison was born in Lorain, Ohio on February 18, 1931. She received her Bachelor's degree from Howard University and a Master's degree from Cornell University. In 1970, she published her first novel, 'The Bluest Eye.' Her most famous novel, 'Beloved,' was published in 1987. She has won numerous awards including the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction in 1988, the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1993, and the American Book Award in 2015.

Michael Phelps is the most decorated Olympian in history, having won 28 medals in his career, including 23 golds. He was born on June 30, 1985 in Baltimore, Maryland. His parents are Richard and Debbie Phelps, and he has two sisters. In 2004, at the age of 19, he won six gold medals at the Olympics in Athens, Greece, breaking Mark Spitz's record of seven gold medals at a single Olympic games. At the 2008 Beijing Olympics, Phelps won eight gold medals and broke his own record of six golds at one Olympic games.

Born in Pasadena, California in 1947, Octavia E. Butler was an American science fiction author and social activist. She wrote short stories and novels that dealt with issues of racism, sexism, and classism. In 2015, she became the first science fiction writer to be awarded a MacArthur 'Genius Grant'.

Born in London, England, Christiane Amanpour is an award-winning journalist and television news anchor. She has worked for CNN since 1983 and was named the network's Chief International Correspondent in 2000. In 2006, she became the host of "This Week with Christiane Amanpour," which airs on ABC News. She has covered numerous major stories including the Gulf War, the Iraq War, and the Arab Spring.

Born in Buenos Aires, Argentina, in 1960, Diego Armando Maradona was one of the greatest football players of all time. He started playing at a young age and made his professional debut at the age of 15. In 1982, he led Argentina to their first ever World Cup victory. His career was cut short due to drug addiction and personal problems. In 2012, he was named as the best player in the world by FIFA.

Born in Grand Rapids, Minnesota in 1922, Judy Garland was the youngest of three children of a vaudeville performer. She started singing at age two and had her own radio program when she was just five years old. In 1935, Garland got her first major movie role in The Wizard of Oz, which earned her an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress. She continued to make films throughout the 1940s, including Meet Me in St. Louis and A Star Is Born. After marrying director Vincente Minnelli in 1945, she gave birth to two daughters. Garland suffered from mental illness and addiction problems and died of a barbiturate overdose in 1969.

Tom Brady was born in San Mateo, California on August 3, 1977. He played football for the University of Michigan, where he was named the team's MVP. In 2000, Brady was drafted by the New England Patriots as the 199th pick. He won his first Super Bowl with the Patriots in 2002 and has since won four more championships. Brady is the NFL's all-time leader in passing yards (65,820) and touchdown passes (467). He is also a three-time league MVP and was named to the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 2015.

Born in 1980, Kim Kardashian is the daughter of Robert and Kris Jenner, who were married in 1976. She was raised in Beverly Hills, California, with her two sisters, Khloe and Kourtney. After graduating from high school, Kim began modeling and later worked as a stylist for celebrities. In 2006, she launched her own line of denim clothing, which has been a success. Kim married NBA player Kris Humphries in 2011, but they divorced after only 72 days of marriage. Kim currently stars in the reality show 'Keeping Up With the Kardashians,' alongside her family.

Born in Nigeria, Hakeem Olajuwon moved to the United States at age 12, and played college basketball for the University of Houston. After leading his team to the NCAA Final Four, he was drafted by the Houston Rockets. In 1985, he became an All-Star, and won the NBA MVP award in 1994. He was inducted into the Basketball Hall of Fame in 2008, and is also known as "The Dream."

Agatha Christie was born in 1890, the daughter of a British army officer. She grew up in various parts of the world and was educated at home. After marrying an American stockbroker, she moved to England. In 1926, Christie published her first novel, 'The Mysterious Affair at Styles.' Her next novel, 'The Murder of Roger Ackroyd,' was published in 1926. She continued writing novels and plays until her death in 1976. Her most famous works are 'And Then There Were None' (1939) and 'Murder on the Orient Express' (1934).

Born in Mississippi in 1935, Elvis Presley's life was filled with hardship and poverty. At age 12, he was sent to live with his grandparents, who raised him as their own. In 1954, Presley was drafted into the U.S. Army, where he served for two years. After returning from the war, he released his first record, "Heartbreak Hotel," which became an instant hit. His career continued to grow, and he became one of the most famous singers in history. He married Priscilla Beaulieu in 1967, and they had two children, Lisa Marie and Riley. In 1973, Presley died of heart failure at the age of 42.

Michael Jackson was born in Gary, Indiana on August 29, 1958, to Joseph and Katherine Jackson. He was the seventh child in the family. When he was four years old, his father took him to live in Los Angeles, where Michael later became a famous singer, dancer, songwriter, and actor. In 1967, Michael's mother died from cancer and his father remarried, resulting in Michael being raised by his grandparents. In 1969, Michael made his first appearance on stage with The Jackson 5. They had several hit songs, such as 'I Want You Back,' 'ABC,' and 'I'll Be There.' In 1979, Michael released his first solo album, 'Off the Wall.' It was followed by 'Thriller' in 1982, which sold more than 65 million copies worldwide and made Jackson the biggest-selling artist of all time.

Born in 1959, Paul Farmer is an American physician and medical anthropologist, who has devoted his life to fighting global poverty. He was born in Newton, Massachusetts, and earned his bachelor's degree from Amherst College, followed by a doctorate from Harvard Medical School. After completing his residency, he traveled to Haiti in 1983 to work on healthcare programs for the poor. Since then, he has founded Partners In Health (PIH), which works in over 20 countries worldwide. PIH is known for its innovative approach to treating patients with infectious diseases, including tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS.

Milton Glaser is an American graphic designer, and is the founder of the New York design firm Milton Glaser Inc. He is known for his work in the 1960s, which included the logo for the New York City subway system. In 1967, he created the 'I (Heart) NY' logo, and it has since become one of the most recognizable logos in the world. The logo has been used in advertising campaigns for New York City, and it is now also featured on t-shirts, posters, and other merchandise.

Born in Atchison, Kansas in 1897, Amelia Earhart was the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean. In 1932, she became the first person to fly solo from Hawaii to California. She disappeared over the Pacific Ocean while attempting to fly around the world in 1937, and was declared legally dead in 1939. She was the first woman to receive the Distinguished Flying Cross, and her autobiography, 'The Fun of It,' became a bestseller.

Born in Detroit, Michigan, on February 4, 1902, Charles Lindbergh was an aviator who became famous for being the first person to cross the Atlantic Ocean by airplane. He was also a World War I pilot and later served as the U.S. Ambassador to Mexico. His son, Charles Augustus Lindbergh Jr., was kidnapped in 1932. The kidnapper demanded $50,000 in ransom money. After his son's death, he became an anti-war activist and advocated against the use of atomic weapons.

Born in Beijing, China in 1963, Jet Li began training in martial arts at the age of 8. At age 17, he won the national kickboxing championship, and soon after that, he was offered a job with the Beijing Wushu Team. After moving to Hong Kong in 1982, Li made his film debut in 'The Shaolin Temple' (1982). He went on to star in numerous films, including 'Once Upon a Time in China' (1991), 'Hero' (2002) and 'Fearless' (2006). Li has also served as a Goodwill Ambassador for the UN Food Programme, and has founded his own charity foundation.

Born in 1982, Yo is a Japanese rapper, DJ, and producer. He has released numerous albums, including 'Yo's Birthday,' 'Yo's Birthday II,' and 'Yo's Birthday III.' In 2012, he won the Best New Artist award at the Japan Record Awards.

Born in 69 BC, Cleopatra was the daughter of Ptolemy XII and his second wife, Cleopatra VII. At age 18, she became queen of Egypt after her father's death. In 51 BC, she married Julius Caesar and gave birth to their son, Caesarion. After Caesar's assassination, Cleopatra became involved with Mark Antony. She bore him three children. In 30 BC, Cleopatra committed suicide by allowing herself to be bitten by an asp.

Born in 1821, Mary Baker Eddy was the founder of the Christian Science church. She was raised in a family that was deeply religious and she was exposed to many different types of religions, including Methodism and Unitarianism. In 1866, Eddy suffered from severe health problems, which led her to search for alternative treatments. She became interested in homeopathy and began practicing it on herself. In 1875, Eddy published a book called "Science and Health with Key to the Scriptures," which was a combination of her beliefs on Christianity and homeopathy. The book was widely read and helped to spread the message of Christian Science. In 1899, Eddy founded the Christian Science church. Today, Christian Science has over 300,000 members in more than 100 countries.

Rafael Nadal was born in Manacor, Spain on June 3, 1986. He is a professional tennis player and is ranked number one in the world. He is also the winner of 15 Grand Slam titles. Nadal's first major tournament victory was at the 2005 French Open, when he defeated Roger Federer in the final. In 2009, he won his first Australian Open and became the first man since Rod Laver to win all four Grand Slams in a single season.

Born in Basel, Switzerland, Roger Federer started playing tennis at the age of eight. He was coached by his father, Robert, until he turned 14. At the age of 17, he won his first Grand Slam title at the 2003 Wimbledon Championship. He also won the US Open and the French Open that year, making him the youngest male to win three Grand Slams in one season. In 2009, he became the first man to win the Grand Slam four times in one year.

Born in 1986, Petra Cortright is an American artist who creates art with video games, and uses the internet as her canvas. Her work often consists of videos of herself playing games like 'Mario Kart' or 'Pokemon Red'. She also makes short animations that are uploaded to YouTube. Cortright was born and raised in Portland, Oregon, and attended the California Institute of the Arts in Los Angeles. In 2010, she won the first ever New Museum Triennial Award for Emerging Artists.

Wolfgang Puck was born in Austria in 1949, and he immigrated to the United States at age 24. He started out as a dishwasher at the Ma Maison restaurant, and then moved on to be a cook at Spago. In 1982, Puck opened his own restaurant, Spago, and it quickly became one of the hottest restaurants in Los Angeles. He has won numerous awards, including the James Beard Award for Best Chef in America in 1990. Puck also has a line of cookware and cookbooks, and has appeared on many television shows, including 'Top Chef' and 'The Today Show.'

Christopher Nolan was born in London, England on July 30, 1970. His parents were British and his father was an actor. He studied film at the University of London and later worked as a film editor before making his directorial debut with 'Following' in 1998. His most recent films include 'Inception', 'Dunkirk', and 'The Dark Knight Trilogy'. Nolan has won multiple awards for his work, including an Academy Award, BAFTA Award, and Golden Globe Award.

Born in 1950, Jenny Holzer is an American artist who creates art with language, sound and light. Her works include installations, public projections and prints. She has worked with many different mediums such as paintings, sculptures, photographs, videos and performances. In the late 1970s, she began using electronic media to create art. In 1982, she started making her famous "Truisms," which were short phrases or statements that appeared on posters and signs around New York City.

Born in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1928, Sol LeWitt is an American artist, sculptor, and writer. He studied at Syracuse University, Yale University, and the Massachusetts College of Art. LeWitt's artworks are known for their simplicity and minimalism. They include wall drawings, sculpture, prints, and books. He is considered to be one of the most influential figures in modern art.

Born in 1981, Zhang Yiming is the co-founder and CEO of the Chinese technology company, Xiaomi. The company was founded in 2010, and has become one of the largest smartphone manufacturers in China. In 2014, the company's revenue reached $12 billion, and it is now worth $45 billion. Xiaomi has been named as the world's most valuable startup by Forbes.

Born in Manhattan, New York City on April 4, 1965, Robert Downey Jr. was raised by his mother and father, who were both actors. After dropping out of high school at age 16, Downey began acting in the early 1980s. He has appeared in over 75 films, including Iron Man, The Avengers, and Captain America: Civil War. His net worth is estimated to be $250 million.
